{{ElectionsNY}}
The '''[[New York City]] mayoral election of 1961''' occurred on Tuesday, November 7, 1961, with incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Mayor of New York City|Mayor]] [[Robert F. Wagner, Jr.]] going on to win a decisive re-election victory for a third term in office.

Wagner defeated the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee, state [[Attorney General of New York|Attorney General]] [[Louis J. Lefkowitz]], and the Citizens Party nominee, [[New York City Comptroller]] [[Lawrence E. Gerosa]].

Wagner received 51.03% of the vote to Lefkowitz's 34.46%, a Democratic victory margin of 16.57%.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York City Mayoral Election 1961 |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=79310|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref>

Gerosa finished in third, with 13.26%.

Gerosa, running with the short-lived "pro-taxpayer"<ref>''To be Mayor of New York: Ethnic Politics in the City'', by Chris McNickle ([[Columbia University Press]], 1993, {{ISBN|0-231-07636-3}}, page 175: free preview was available on June 20, 2008 at https://books.google.com/books?id=ONlCSIMrV_kC&pg=PA175)</ref> Citizens Party, billed himself as the "real Democrat" in the race, and took many [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] votes, finishing relatively strongly for a [[Third Party (United States)|third party]] candidate.

Wagner won decisive majorities in [[Manhattan]], [[Brooklyn]], and the [[Bronx]], and won a plurality in [[Queens]]. Lefkowitz eked out a narrow 1-point plurality win in [[Staten Island]].

Wagner was also the nominee of the [[Liberal Party of New York|Liberal Party]], and additionally ran on the Brotherhood ballot line. Lefkowitz also ran on the Nonpartisan and Civic Action ballot lines, while Gerosa also ran on the [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] ballot line.

After being supported by the [[Tammany Hall]] machine in his [[New York City mayoral election, 1953|1953]] and [[New York City mayoral election, 1957|1957]] elections, Wagner broke with Tammany Hall in 1961, defeating the Democratic Party [[Power broker (politics)|power brokers']] chosen candidate, [[Arthur Levitt, Sr.|Arthur Levitt]], in the Democratic primary and then going on to win a third term in the general election. Wagner's victory thus ultimately signified the decline of the power of [[political machine]]s in New York City.<ref>''To be Mayor of New York: Ethnic Politics in the City'', by Chris McNickle ([[Columbia University Press]], 1993, {{ISBN|0-231-07636-3}}, page 175: free preview was available on April 26, 2014 at https://books.google.com/books?id=ONlCSIMrV_kC&pg=PA175)</ref>

Wagner would be sworn into his third and final term in January 1962.

